          "title": "Jacob's failure of leadership",
          "body": "The patriarch of the covenant family — the man who wrestled with God and received the name Israel (Genesis 32:28) — hears that his daughter has been sexually violated and 'kept silent until they came in' (34:5). His sons act in his absence; negotiations happen without his leadership; the massacre occurs without his command. When he finally speaks (34:30), his entire speech is self-referential: 'you have brought trouble on me... they will attack me and I will be destroyed, I and my household.' He does not mention Dinah. He does not invoke God. He does not articulate a moral standard. He calculates his own survival. Swindoll notes in his Genesis commentary that this is one of the most damaging portraits of passive fatherhood in all of Scripture. Jacob's spiritual and moral passivity in chapter 34 is the direct result of his failure to keep the family near the altar — a failure God corrects in 35:1."
