          "body": "Circumcision was given to Abraham in Genesis 17 as the sign of the covenant — the mark of belonging to the God who had called Abraham out of Ur and who would give him the land and multiply his seed. When Simeon and Levi demand circumcision as the condition of intermarriage (34:15), they invoke the covenant sign — but not for covenant purposes. They have no intention of making the Shechemites covenant partners; they intend to use the covenant sign to render the men physically vulnerable. This is among the chapter's darkest theological notes. The very mark God gave to distinguish His people becomes a weapon for deception and slaughter. Jacob himself will name the consequence in his dying blessing (Genesis 49:5-7): Simeon and Levi are cursed, their anger condemned as fierce and cruel, and they will be scattered in Israel. The desecration of circumcision here is the theological ground for that tribal judgment."
