          "body": "Hamor's speech to his city gate (34:20-23) inadvertently exposes the real danger Jacob's family faces. His public offer sounds magnanimous: these men are peaceful, the land is large, let us become one people (34:21-22). But his closing argument to his townsmen is entirely mercenary: 'will not their livestock and their property and all their animals be ours?' (34:23). The covenant family's absorption into Canaanite culture was not going to produce a redemptive transformation of the nations — it was going to produce the opposite: the swallowing of a small, outnumbered covenant community into a larger pagan one, with their wealth redistributed. Deuteronomy will later articulate the theological principle explicitly (7:3-4): intermarriage with Canaanite nations turns the heart away from the LORD. Hamor's speech reveals why. The Shechemites were not converting to Israel's God; they were extending their commercial and territorial dominion."
