        "range": "34:1-7",
        "excerpt": "When Shechem the son of Hamor the Hivite, the prince of the land, saw her, he took her and lay with her by force.",
        "body": "The chapter opens with two verses of merciless narrative economy. Dinah goes out — one Hebrew verb — and the next verse names four sequential acts: Shechem saw, took, lay with her by force, and was attracted to her (34:2-3). The sequence is precise and brutal. The verb translated 'by force' (*anah*) is the standard Hebrew term for sexual violation or humiliation; it is used of Tamar's rape by Amnon in 2 Samuel 13:14 and of the atrocity at Gibeah in Judges 19-20. There is no ambiguity about the nature of the act.\n\nThe chapter then stages three distinct responses to the same event, and their contrast is the narrator's first theological move. Shechem, the offender, responds with romantic attachment (34:3) and an immediate demand for marriage (34:4) — he frames the crime as the prologue to a love story. Hamor, the offending father, moves to diplomacy (34:6). Jacob, the victimized father, keeps silent (34:5). The sons respond with grief and fury (34:7). Every response reveals a character; none of the three responses to Shechem's crime includes the one thing the text quietly invites: prayer, divine consultation, or reference to the covenant God.\n\nVerse 7 is the narrator's own editorial insertion: the brothers were 'very angry because he had done a disgraceful thing (*nevalah*) in Israel by lying with Jacob's daughter, for such a thing ought not to be done.' The phrase 'in Israel' is anachronistic — Israel as a nation does not yet exist — but it is theologically deliberate. The narrator is projecting forward: this act violates the moral order that will eventually be codified in Israel's law (cf. Deuteronomy 22:28-29). The brothers' anger is grounded in a legitimate moral standard, not in tribal pride alone. But the narrator's validation of their anger does not extend to their response.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Anah* (34:2, 'by force') — the standard Pentateuchal term for sexual violation; its use here is unambiguous. *Nevalah* (34:7, 'disgraceful thing') — a wanton social outrage; the same word is used of Tamar's rape (2 Samuel 13:12), Achan's theft (Joshua 7:15), and the Gibeah atrocity (Judges 20:6, 10). It denotes an act that tears the social and moral fabric of the covenant community."
