        "body": "The chapter's central section (34:8-23) is a study in the gap between diplomatic language and real motive. Hamor opens the negotiation with what sounds like a reasonable proposal: his son loves Dinah, let there be intermarriage, free movement, land acquisition (34:8-10). Shechem adds personal entreaty and an offer of unlimited bridal payment (34:11-12). The terms are generous. The tone is conciliatory. But the narrator has already told the reader that the brothers' response is 'deceit' (34:13) — and the subsequent speech of Hamor to his city (34:20-23) reveals that the deceit runs in both directions.\n\nWhen Hamor addresses his city gate, the civic language of 'becoming one people' (34:22) is the public argument. But the closing sentence to his townsmen (34:23) is the real argument: 'Will not their livestock and their property and all their animals be ours?' The intermarriage proposal was never primarily about love or cultural integration — it was a merger-and-acquisition strategy. Jacob's family would bring wealth, labor, and commercial networks into the Shechemite city, and Shechem's city would eventually absorb them. From Hamor's perspective, circumcision is a reasonable price for the wealth it would deliver.\n\nThe brothers' response (34:14-17) invokes a real concern — intermarriage with the uncircumcised would dissolve the covenant boundary that distinguished Israel — but the circumcision demand is not a genuine offer of covenant inclusion. The narrator's label 'mirmah' (deceit, 34:13) is placed before the brothers speak, not after, so the reader knows before the speech is given that it is a pretext. They have no intention of giving their daughters or becoming one people; they intend to use the recovery period after circumcision as a tactical window.\n\nThe double deception — Hamor's covetousness masked as diplomacy, the brothers' revenge masked as covenant concern — exposes a world where the covenant sign has become currency in a negotiation that has nothing to do with God. Neither party invokes the LORD. Neither party consults divine law. Both parties use the language of covenant (circumcision, marriage, becoming one people) for entirely non-covenant purposes.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mirmah* (deceit, 34:13) — Jacob used the same word (*mirmah*) in Genesis 27:35 when Esau accused him of deceit in stealing the blessing. The sons have inherited and weaponized their father's besetting sin. *Chashaq* (longs for, 34:8) — a verb of deep attachment, used elsewhere of God's love for Israel (Deuteronomy 7:7) and Solomon's desire for foreign women (1 Kings 9:19). Its use here for Shechem's desire is ironic: the same word for covenant love describes the rapist's post-violation attachment."
