        "body": "Three verses accomplish the massacre, and their brevity is itself the narrator's judgment. 'On the third day, when they were in pain' (34:25) — a single temporal clause establishes the tactical calculation. The third day of post-circumcision recovery was, in the ancient context, the peak of inflammation and incapacitation. Simeon and Levi chose this window deliberately. The narrator does not commend the strategy; he records it with the same clinical detachment he used for the assault in verse 2.\n\nThe identification 'Dinah's brothers' (34:25) is the chapter's most intimate verse. Throughout the chapter, Dinah is 'Jacob's daughter' (from the patriarch's perspective) or the object of negotiation. Here, for the first time, the narrator calls Simeon and Levi 'Dinah's brothers' — and the phrase humanizes the relationship in a way the rest of the chapter has not. Their act, however disproportionate, proceeds from a real sibling bond. They are avenging a sister, not executing a policy.\n\nBut 'every male' is not proportional justice. Shechem committed the crime; Hamor engineered the exploitation; the men of the city consented to circumcision under false pretenses. But the men of the city did not rape Dinah, did not devise the cover-up, and were killed while incapacitated by a religious procedure they had agreed to in good faith. The massacre goes far beyond retributive justice, and the narrator — and ultimately Jacob's dying words in Genesis 49:5-7 — will say so.\n\nVerse 26 records that Simeon and Levi killed Hamor and Shechem specifically, then 'took Dinah from Shechem's house.' The retrieval of Dinah is the only act in the chapter that corresponds to its stated motivation. Everything that follows in verses 27-29 does not.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Betach* (unawares, 34:25) — literally 'in security, in confidence, trusting.' The irony is sharp: the Shechemites consented to circumcision because they trusted Jacob's family's offer of peaceful integration (34:21 — 'these men are at peace with us'). They were killed precisely because they trusted. The same word *betach* is used in Jeremiah 49:31 for nations living in false security — always a signal of impending judgment."
