        "body": "Three verses document what the other brothers — not Simeon and Levi alone — did after the massacre. They 'looted the city' (34:27), taking flocks, herds, donkeys, goods from city and field (34:28), and then captured and plundered 'all their wealth and all their little ones and their wives' (34:29). The escalation from Simeon and Levi's targeted killing to the brothers' comprehensive plunder is not incidental — it is the chapter's moral completion.\n\nThe narrator attaches 'because they had defiled their sister' (34:27) to the looting, using the same causal chain he used in 34:7 and 34:13. But the causal connection is now strained. The Shechemite women and children who are captured in verse 29 did not defile Dinah. The cattle and donkeys who are taken in verse 28 did not defile Dinah. The looting has moved from response-to-crime to exploitation-of-weakness — exactly what Hamor did when he saw Jacob's family as a commercial opportunity.\n\nThe parallel is deliberate and damning. Hamor's real motive was covetousness of Jacob's livestock (34:23). The brothers end the chapter possessing Shechem's livestock, property, women, and children. The covenant family has, in the space of one chapter, become what they were avenging. This is not the narrator's endorsement of moral equivalence between rape and massacre — the crimes are different in kind. It is the narrator's insistence that unchecked vengeance does not produce righteousness; it produces a mirror image of the original sin.\n\nCalvin (Commentary on Genesis) notes that while Simeon and Levi's anger at Dinah's violation was not without justice, 'the cruelty of the punishment far exceeded the bounds of moderation.' Peter Craigie and Walter Brueggemann similarly observe that the brothers' action is neither authorized by divine command nor proportionate to the offense. The plunder in particular — taking women and children — places Jacob's family in the position of slave-takers, which is precisely the kind of social violence the later Mosaic code would restrict."
